00:04:59.320 --> 00:05:02.679
So like I mentioned, two years ago,

00:05:02.679 --> 00:05:04.119
there was just two developers, right?

00:05:04.119 --> 00:05:05.559
It was me and another guy.

00:05:05.559 --> 00:05:09.799
And we had just started working with Shiny at that point.

00:05:09.799 --> 00:05:11.640
Up until then, markdowns were sufficient,

00:05:11.640 --> 00:05:13.399
data pulls were sufficient,

00:05:13.399 --> 00:05:14.559
but the business was growing

00:05:14.559 --> 00:05:16.119
and they wanted more interactivity

00:05:16.440 --> 00:05:18.399
and granular looks into their data.

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:23.920
And part of this was we had legacy code

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:25.399
that was being transferred to our department.

00:05:25.399 --> 00:05:27.880
So the data science team had built around

00:05:27.880 --> 00:05:30.799
these six dashboards that were pretty complex, right?

00:05:30.799 --> 00:05:34.679
They have six to eight different tabs on a sidebar.

00:05:34.679 --> 00:05:39.000
They all do kind of different UI layouts and backends.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.880
And what we noticed was that these six dashboards

00:05:41.880 --> 00:05:44.720
were all coded slightly differently, right?

00:05:44.959 --> 00:05:47.119
So the look and feel is pretty similar,

00:05:47.119 --> 00:05:50.079
but some of them had pure API backends,

00:05:50.079 --> 00:05:52.320
some of them used SQL instead.

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:54.559
They had similarly named functions

00:05:54.559 --> 00:05:56.160
that did entirely different purposes

00:05:56.160 --> 00:05:57.880
on the different dashboards.

00:05:57.880 --> 00:06:01.519
Some used selectize input versus picker input.

00:06:01.519 --> 00:06:03.519
And so the challenge was,

00:06:03.519 --> 00:06:06.239
you spend all this time focusing on a dashboard,

00:06:07.279 --> 00:06:08.480
but when you go to the next dashboard,

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:11.600
you can only port like 40% of that knowledge

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:14.239
with the new intricacies in the new dashboard.

00:06:14.839 --> 00:06:17.880
And the new dashboard you're working on, right?

00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:20.559
And so the other challenge at the same time we were facing

00:06:20.559 --> 00:06:23.399
is we were about to hire four new developers

00:06:23.399 --> 00:06:26.079
that had various backgrounds and skillsets,

00:06:26.079 --> 00:06:27.600
but they all had minimal experience

00:06:27.600 --> 00:06:30.760
with R and Shiny specifically, right?

00:06:30.760 --> 00:06:35.000
And so the questions that we were trying to answer

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:37.839
immediately was how do we standardize our workflow

00:06:37.839 --> 00:06:39.480
so we can minimize future tech debt

00:06:39.480 --> 00:06:41.359
with our dashboards that we build?

00:06:41.359 --> 00:06:44.279
And secondarily, how can I get new hires

00:06:44.279 --> 00:06:45.480
to understand what we're doing

00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:48.200
and start building dashboards very quickly, right?

00:06:49.160 --> 00:06:54.160
And so that, when I was researching that problem,

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:57.279
we learned about what the Golem package was.

00:06:57.279 --> 00:06:59.320
And currently the Golem package

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:01.399
has a very fleshed out GitHub repo.

00:07:01.399 --> 00:07:02.880
It has a published book

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:05.760
that you can either purchase or view online.

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:07.040
But when I looked at it two years ago,

00:07:07.040 --> 00:07:09.440
it was just this little book down

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:14.440
with five or so sections that had bare bones concepts

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:17.600
and they're still fleshing out the process.

00:07:17.600 --> 00:07:20.760
But the idea of Golem has stayed the same, right?

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:23.720
They're trying to build modular dashboards

00:07:23.720 --> 00:07:26.239
with a package-based framework.

00:07:26.239 --> 00:07:28.440
And before we go into what that means,

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:30.440
I just wanna cover those concepts really quick

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:31.640
with a couple of slides.

00:07:32.839 --> 00:07:36.359
So all Shiny apps have the same thing in common, right?

00:07:36.359 --> 00:07:38.839
They use a UI to create a layout

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:42.000
and then a server to connect data to that layout.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:43.399
And so when you build Shiny dashboards,

00:07:43.399 --> 00:07:46.160
there's basically three ways you do so, right?

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:48.200
The first method is the all-in-one approach, right?

00:07:48.200 --> 00:07:49.760
So you can make a very simple dashboard

00:07:49.760 --> 00:07:53.359
with an app.r file, all your codes in one place,

00:07:53.359 --> 00:07:56.559
and it makes simple dashboards.

00:07:57.480 --> 00:07:58.880
When you add more complexity,

00:07:58.880 --> 00:08:02.160
you kind of split the UI and server into their own files

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:04.559
because that separates their purposes cleanly, right?

00:08:04.559 --> 00:08:07.000
The UI has all the layouts in it,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:08.799
the server files all like the code backend

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:11.399
and so you know that each of those is referring

00:08:11.399 --> 00:08:14.040
to its very specific parts.

00:08:14.040 --> 00:08:17.000
And then eventually it lives in like a single folder, right?

00:08:18.119 --> 00:08:21.079
The third method is called modularization.

00:08:21.079 --> 00:08:22.359
And what this does is,

00:08:22.359 --> 00:08:24.640
let's say you wanna build a dashboard

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:27.920
that serves like four different parts of the business, right?

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:31.640
Sales, product, marketing, and like some executive view.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:33.880
If you try and put all of that into one server file,

00:08:33.880 --> 00:08:36.239
that's going to be a very large server file,

00:08:36.239 --> 00:08:37.880
which isn't very helpful.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:40.919
So modularization sticks all these sections

00:08:40.919 --> 00:08:42.679
into their own UI and server

00:08:42.679 --> 00:08:44.520
for each individual dashboard piece.

00:08:45.679 --> 00:08:47.840
Additionally, this avoids namespace conflicts

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:50.719
that you can sometimes run into with the other methods.

00:08:50.719 --> 00:08:52.719
But the key point here is that

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:55.520
when you modularize your dashboards,

00:08:55.520 --> 00:08:58.960
the UI and server become self-contained functions

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:00.919
that your dashboard will eventually call

00:09:00.919 --> 00:09:02.520
when it builds its dashboard.

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:06.559
So keep that phrase in mind as we go to the next slide.

00:09:08.080 --> 00:09:10.479
R packages, if you've never built an R package,

00:09:10.479 --> 00:09:12.400
you've certainly installed one.

00:09:12.400 --> 00:09:14.159
And what a package actually is,

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:18.880
is it's a bundle of files, datasets, unit tests,

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:21.200
and individual functions, right?

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:24.239
Whether you're using dplyr or ggplot2,

00:09:24.239 --> 00:09:26.479
if you look into their GitHub repos,

00:09:26.479 --> 00:09:29.599
all of their functions are tiny little discrete R scripts

00:09:29.599 --> 00:09:33.119
that are bundled together as a package, right?

00:09:33.119 --> 00:09:36.239
And so there's that phrase again, self-contained functions.

00:09:36.239 --> 00:09:41.119
And so what Golem does, what it's trying to do basically,

00:09:41.119 --> 00:09:42.559
is it looks at the commonalities

00:09:42.559 --> 00:09:45.359
between modularization and package frameworks.

00:09:45.359 --> 00:09:46.799
In other words, Golem says,

00:09:46.799 --> 00:09:49.599
well, if all my modules are just functions already

00:09:49.599 --> 00:09:51.919
and a package is just a bundle of functions,

00:09:51.919 --> 00:09:54.320
why can't I just make my dashboard a package

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:56.479
and run it and deploy it that way?

00:09:56.479 --> 00:09:58.960
And the advantage to that is packages

00:09:58.960 --> 00:10:00.520
are very standardized, right?

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:04.640
There are specific folders and directories and locations

00:10:04.640 --> 00:10:06.719
where files go within an R package.

00:10:08.799 --> 00:10:10.479
Because of that though,

00:10:10.479 --> 00:10:13.159
Golem has no shortage of creation options, right?

00:10:13.159 --> 00:10:14.919
So if you just install Golem

00:10:14.919 --> 00:10:17.039
and try to run with their workflow, right,

00:10:17.039 --> 00:10:20.280
there's tons of different deployment types you can do,

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:23.799
either RPUBs, RStudio Connect, Docker,

00:10:23.799 --> 00:10:27.280
I believe they even do like GitHub Pages at some point.

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:28.840
There's different unit tests you can create

00:10:28.840 --> 00:10:31.799
either at like the module or the app level.

00:10:31.799 --> 00:10:33.799
Again, various ways to import files

00:10:33.799 --> 00:10:36.520
and different configurations for your actual app.

00:10:36.520 --> 00:10:39.880
And so when I was testing this out,

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:41.640
I'm trying to answer those two questions, right?

00:10:41.640 --> 00:10:45.320
Does it solve those two challenges we're facing?

00:10:45.320 --> 00:10:47.840
Standardization, absolutely, right?

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:49.479
Packages, like I mentioned,

00:10:49.479 --> 00:10:51.919
they have to be built a certain way in order to work, right?

00:10:51.919 --> 00:10:54.719
They have to have an instance folder, a man folder,

00:10:54.719 --> 00:10:57.159
namespaces, descriptions, all that is standard

00:10:57.159 --> 00:11:00.200
across like every single R package that's ever built.

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:04.200
But because of all these complex options,

00:11:04.200 --> 00:11:06.599
it doesn't do a good job of communication

00:11:06.599 --> 00:11:08.479
to new developers or people that don't have

00:11:08.479 --> 00:11:11.080
a lot of experience with R and R Shiny.

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:12.799
And that's by design.

00:11:12.799 --> 00:11:16.000
If you look at the first page of the Golem book,

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
it actually says, you know, if you're reading this,

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.840
you have some intermediate advanced level

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:21.960
of how Shiny works on the backend.

00:11:21.960 --> 00:11:25.640
And this is trying to explore more possibilities there.

00:11:25.640 --> 00:11:28.239
So what do I need to do though?

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:32.919
So we built Gravelr to kind of address that complexity.

00:11:32.919 --> 00:11:34.880
We take away all those options,

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:36.719
we strip them down to the bare minimum and say,

00:11:36.719 --> 00:11:39.960
here's these defaults, let's run with those defaults

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:41.799
and you'll be good to go, right?

00:11:43.799 --> 00:11:45.320
If you're curious about the name,

00:11:45.320 --> 00:11:50.320
so I'm a huge Pokemon nerd and Golem itself is,

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:52.280
well, I don't believe the Golem package

00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:53.799
was named after the Pokemon Golem,

00:11:53.799 --> 00:11:57.559
but if I'm taking this, you know, big complex package

00:11:57.559 --> 00:11:59.159
and I'm making it simpler,

00:11:59.159 --> 00:12:01.000
the simpler version of Golem in the Pokemon world

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
is called Gravelr, so that's the name there.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:06.359
And I'm pleased to announce that Gravelr

00:12:06.359 --> 00:12:08.479
is available on GitHub currently.

00:12:08.479 --> 00:12:10.880
So you can search either GitHub on,

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:12.200
or not search GitHub on GitHub,

00:12:12.200 --> 00:12:14.200
search Gravelr on GitHub.

00:12:15.320 --> 00:12:18.679
You can install it with devtools, colon, colon,

00:12:18.679 --> 00:12:22.640
install underscore GitHub, ghcarlallen, slash Gravelr.

00:12:22.640 --> 00:12:25.440
It's in a bunch of links in the blog post and whatever.

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:28.679
So you can install it for yourself there.

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:33.679
And so with that, we will switch to my R screen.

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:40.679
