00:25:04.560 --> 00:25:07.280
So in Golem, their philosophy is,

00:25:07.280 --> 00:25:10.719
you want to abstract away as much as you can

00:25:10.719 --> 00:25:13.119
from even your module code, right?

00:25:13.119 --> 00:25:14.160
So for example, you know,

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:18.439
you can have a bunch of different charts or tables in this,

00:25:18.439 --> 00:25:21.239
but at the moment your code starts to repeat itself,

00:25:21.239 --> 00:25:24.199
you want to put that inside of a function

00:25:24.199 --> 00:25:28.119
to make this as clean and compact as possible.

00:25:28.119 --> 00:25:31.560
And so it's a hard concept to explain just verbally.

00:25:31.560 --> 00:25:33.239
So if I'm going, so excuse me,

00:25:33.239 --> 00:25:36.920
I'm going to switch to the actual Graveler package

00:25:36.920 --> 00:25:38.319
because inside of it,

00:25:38.319 --> 00:25:42.319
there is an example dashboard that's fleshed out

00:25:42.319 --> 00:25:43.319
called Geodude.

00:25:45.359 --> 00:25:47.959
And it itself has its own little modules, right?

00:25:48.479 --> 00:25:50.040
So I'll show you what it looks like by default.

00:25:52.520 --> 00:25:53.359
Oops.

00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:56.119
Set my working directory.

00:26:00.239 --> 00:26:01.280
And there you go.

00:26:03.920 --> 00:26:05.520
So this is the default example.

00:26:05.520 --> 00:26:09.079
You can also run this yourself with, I believe,

00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:11.719
what is it, Graveler.

00:26:14.479 --> 00:26:16.959
Geodude example as well with no parameters in it.

00:26:18.959 --> 00:26:21.560
But so in this first tab, you know,

00:26:21.560 --> 00:26:23.800
you notice that there are four graphs here, right?

00:26:23.800 --> 00:26:25.599
Representing ants, ants, combs, quartet.

00:26:25.599 --> 00:26:29.359
So with a couple of GG plot leads and whatnot.

00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:31.680
So how did I build this, right?

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:34.640
Did I write a GG plot code for different times?

00:26:34.640 --> 00:26:36.920
No, because, you know, let's say someone tells you,

00:26:36.920 --> 00:26:39.520
I want to change those dots from a horrendous lime green

00:26:39.520 --> 00:26:41.839
to an actual human visible color.

00:26:43.280 --> 00:26:46.599
So in my module, here's my UI, right?

00:26:46.599 --> 00:26:49.520
I have just a two by two grade of charts.

00:26:50.439 --> 00:26:53.359
And you'll notice in my plot leads renders,

00:26:53.359 --> 00:26:55.839
I have my own custom function here.

00:26:55.839 --> 00:26:58.359
So I have my dataset and it pipes into a function.

00:26:58.359 --> 00:27:00.719
And that's what this FCT display file is for.

00:27:00.719 --> 00:27:03.800
It's to put all of your functions into one place

00:27:03.800 --> 00:27:06.640
so that if you need to edit parts of your dashboard,

00:27:06.640 --> 00:27:09.920
you only need to edit like one piece of the code, right?

00:27:09.920 --> 00:27:11.000
Where it's duplicated.

00:27:12.239 --> 00:27:13.079
So in this case, you know,

00:27:13.079 --> 00:27:15.239
let's say I want to change it back to orange.

00:27:17.239 --> 00:27:18.959
Now I can save this, rerun the dashboard

00:27:18.959 --> 00:27:21.359
and it should work just fine.

00:27:28.920 --> 00:27:29.760
And there you go.

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:32.040
All four graphs update with the new orange color.

00:27:32.040 --> 00:27:34.040
This applies to any, you know, GG plot option

00:27:34.040 --> 00:27:35.280
or data table option

00:27:35.280 --> 00:27:38.880
or whatever functionality you have in your data.

00:27:40.439 --> 00:27:44.800
The other advantage to adding functions to your FCT file

00:27:44.800 --> 00:27:48.280
is everyone's favorite documentation, right?

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:50.280
Dashboards and their functionalities at this level

00:27:50.280 --> 00:27:52.280
can become incredibly complex.

00:27:52.280 --> 00:27:54.959
And so it's always good to have functionality

00:27:54.959 --> 00:27:56.199
or excuse me, functions

00:27:57.359 --> 00:27:59.319
and documentation for those functions

00:27:59.319 --> 00:28:01.319
so that yourself or other people

00:28:01.319 --> 00:28:03.959
reading your dashboard code six months down the road

00:28:03.959 --> 00:28:04.800
will understand, you know,

00:28:04.800 --> 00:28:06.760
what this code is actually trying to do.

00:28:07.640 --> 00:28:11.239
And the other benefit is, you know, if you recall,

00:28:11.239 --> 00:28:13.920
if we run these lines,

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:18.479
I should be able to export from my package

00:28:18.479 --> 00:28:19.479
and look at that.

00:28:19.479 --> 00:28:21.479
There's my custom function.

00:28:21.479 --> 00:28:23.359
Guess what happens when I put the question mark

00:28:23.359 --> 00:28:24.199
in front of it?

00:28:25.079 --> 00:28:27.119
It builds the actual help documentation

00:28:27.119 --> 00:28:30.079
per Roxygen documentation for code.

00:28:30.079 --> 00:28:33.199
So all of this workflow with Golem and whatnot

00:28:33.199 --> 00:28:35.959
is trying to help you standardize

00:28:35.959 --> 00:28:37.520
your package development,

00:28:37.520 --> 00:28:39.079
standardize your dashboard development,

00:28:39.079 --> 00:28:42.079
actually create documentation for packages down the road.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:48.199
Finally, before we get into a little more customization,

00:28:50.920 --> 00:28:53.319
there is the final file that we had open,

00:28:53.319 --> 00:28:54.719
which was this O2 deploy.

00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:59.000
So what O2 deploy does is

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:01.920
when you publish your dashboards on RStudio Connect,

00:29:01.920 --> 00:29:05.400
they break for good reason

00:29:05.400 --> 00:29:07.839
because they need to have different environment variables

00:29:07.839 --> 00:29:10.800
to connect either to like database credentials

00:29:10.800 --> 00:29:11.839
or if you're using pins,

00:29:11.839 --> 00:29:14.280
you need to have your API key in there somewhere.

00:29:15.239 --> 00:29:17.680
And RStudio, by design,

00:29:17.680 --> 00:29:20.239
you can't like set these beforehand, right?

00:29:20.239 --> 00:29:22.800
So you have to publish and then add them after the fact.

00:29:22.800 --> 00:29:25.880
So what this does is it does a programmatic, right?

00:29:25.880 --> 00:29:29.319
You can go in and add your environment variables

00:29:29.319 --> 00:29:32.479
by yourself, by hand, by adding the name and the value.

00:29:32.479 --> 00:29:35.880
What this does is it uses the Connect API library,

00:29:35.880 --> 00:29:37.560
which I believe is still in development mode.

00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:39.119
So it's not a CRAN package yet,

00:29:41.079 --> 00:29:41.959
but you can load this.

00:29:41.959 --> 00:29:43.520
You can load your custom URLs.

00:29:44.439 --> 00:29:48.160
Ours will be snap finance, whatever, whatever URL.

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:51.199
And then you can connect to the server,

00:29:52.119 --> 00:29:53.719
excuse me, you set the server variables,

00:29:53.719 --> 00:29:55.400
you connect to the server,

00:29:55.400 --> 00:29:59.040
then you find the ID for that piece of content

00:29:59.040 --> 00:29:59.880
you're deploying.

00:30:01.160 --> 00:30:02.479
You can paste that whenever,

00:30:02.479 --> 00:30:05.319
and then you can add the environment right here, right?

00:30:05.319 --> 00:30:08.479
So in this example, I'm finding whatever I just published.

00:30:08.479 --> 00:30:11.439
I get the environment for that published content

00:30:11.479 --> 00:30:13.719
and I add a new variable called key.

00:30:13.719 --> 00:30:15.319
And then I set my own, right?

00:30:15.319 --> 00:30:18.160
Set it equal to whatever my API key is personally.

00:30:19.280 --> 00:30:20.880
So that saves us a lot of time

00:30:20.880 --> 00:30:23.359
with deploying stuff in RStudio Connect.

00:30:24.920 --> 00:30:27.359
But I imagine you're probably asking yourself at some point,

00:30:27.359 --> 00:30:28.959
well, this is great,

00:30:28.959 --> 00:30:31.400
but I don't want this like brown and gray dashboard, right?

00:30:31.400 --> 00:30:34.800
I have very cool purple or blue or yellow business, right?

00:30:34.800 --> 00:30:37.119
I want to brand my own dashboards.

00:30:38.040 --> 00:30:40.680
So if you go into this theme file right here

00:30:40.719 --> 00:30:41.680
at the very bottom,

00:30:42.719 --> 00:30:44.479
that's where you can just set your colors.

00:30:44.479 --> 00:30:45.800
So there's three colors you can do,

00:30:45.800 --> 00:30:47.359
primary, accent, and secondary.

00:30:48.479 --> 00:30:50.880
You can omit these entirely and just kind of, you know,

00:30:50.880 --> 00:30:54.800
customize everything line by line.

00:30:54.800 --> 00:30:58.160
I don't feel like you need to do that, but be my guest.

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:00.040
So if I just change these colors to,

00:31:02.560 --> 00:31:04.880
I don't even know, so many hex codes.

00:31:04.880 --> 00:31:07.640
We'll go that red and black.

00:31:07.640 --> 00:31:09.199
So if I run my dashboard again,

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:12.560
it will update with these colors.

00:31:12.560 --> 00:31:14.920
So my primary is this dark red,

00:31:14.920 --> 00:31:16.760
this accent is this bright red,

00:31:16.760 --> 00:31:18.800
and then there's this like black bar on the left

00:31:18.800 --> 00:31:20.520
for this sidebar option here.

00:31:21.520 --> 00:31:24.439
Again, there's more customizability you can do,

00:31:24.439 --> 00:31:26.920
but that's what I've deemed sufficient

00:31:26.920 --> 00:31:29.119
for the average user is those three colors.

00:31:32.280 --> 00:31:33.880
As well as the logo,

00:31:33.880 --> 00:31:36.160
let's say you have your own custom logo to do,

00:31:36.680 --> 00:31:39.280
just like in a standard Shiny app,

00:31:39.280 --> 00:31:43.719
all of the external assets are in the instaapp www folder.

00:31:43.719 --> 00:31:45.920
So you just add your logo here

00:31:45.920 --> 00:31:50.920
and replace the header value with the new file path.

00:31:51.680 --> 00:31:54.520
So here's the file exists,

00:31:54.520 --> 00:31:57.439
but then if I go into the header back in the R folder,

00:31:58.839 --> 00:32:00.119
here's that file path is.

00:32:00.119 --> 00:32:01.439
So I would just replace this with, you know,

00:32:01.439 --> 00:32:06.319
your logo, SVG, PNG, JPEG, whatever.

00:32:07.319 --> 00:32:09.160
You can also attach URLs.

00:32:09.160 --> 00:32:11.599
So whenever we publish content,

00:32:11.599 --> 00:32:15.760
the title and the logo will link back to our content page.

00:32:15.760 --> 00:32:17.920
So instead of like hitting the back button

00:32:17.920 --> 00:32:19.560
or anything like that,

00:32:19.560 --> 00:32:20.920
they can just like right click the title,

00:32:20.920 --> 00:32:23.400
open a new tab back to the content page.

00:32:23.400 --> 00:32:26.000
By default, it just goes to RStudio's products page.

00:32:27.280 --> 00:32:29.400
So you can change those however you want.

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:33.880
But with that, I believe that's it

00:32:33.880 --> 00:32:38.319
for like the Gravelr dashboard workflow itself.

00:32:38.319 --> 00:32:39.959
Again, I'm not gonna go into, you know,

00:32:39.959 --> 00:32:43.920
creating UI elements or pin calls or anything like that.

00:32:43.920 --> 00:32:45.599
Cause that's, you know, you can research,

00:32:45.599 --> 00:32:47.119
there's plenty of better documentation

00:32:47.119 --> 00:32:49.239
than I could ever make out there for that.

00:32:50.560 --> 00:32:53.079
So we'll switch back to the PowerPoint real quick.

00:32:56.760 --> 00:32:58.599
That's the part where it goes back here.

00:32:59.079 --> 00:33:00.800
So potential enhancements, you know,

00:33:00.800 --> 00:33:03.079
if some of you've worked with this kind of, you know,

00:33:03.079 --> 00:33:06.000
dashboarding or customization before,

00:33:06.000 --> 00:33:09.040
you might have thought of these ideas already.

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:11.880
So as far as, you know, with any code,

00:33:11.880 --> 00:33:13.040
there's always improvements to be made.

00:33:13.040 --> 00:33:14.359
Here's what I've thought of

00:33:14.359 --> 00:33:16.439
for the Gravelr package immediately.

00:33:16.439 --> 00:33:18.800
So as of like Shiny 1.5,

00:33:18.800 --> 00:33:20.760
there's a new method of calling modules.

00:33:20.760 --> 00:33:22.520
So instead of the actual call module function,

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:26.040
there's I think module server is what it does.

00:33:26.040 --> 00:33:29.000
It has a simpler syntax and understanding.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:31.239
So it'd be cool if I could convert it to that.

00:33:32.560 --> 00:33:35.000
Obviously with the dashboard theme package,

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:36.760
and you have those colors and that customization,

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:40.040
but BSLib has been integrated with Shiny already.

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:42.640
And so you can use that more intuitively

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:44.920
and create cleaner colors and layouts.

00:33:44.920 --> 00:33:46.199
Again, at the time when I built this,

00:33:46.199 --> 00:33:49.400
none of these things existed two years ago.

00:33:49.400 --> 00:33:52.599
And then finally, you know, packages live on testing, right?

00:33:52.599 --> 00:33:53.880
The more complex your dashboard is,

00:33:53.920 --> 00:33:57.359
the more points of breakage you're creating itself.

00:33:57.359 --> 00:34:00.239
And so if we can somehow, you know, connect unit tests

00:34:01.520 --> 00:34:03.560
to be put on these like dashboard packages,

00:34:03.560 --> 00:34:04.400
that would be great.

00:34:04.400 --> 00:34:06.319
It's just one of those areas that,

00:34:06.319 --> 00:34:08.239
again, I don't really have a fundamental understanding

00:34:08.239 --> 00:34:09.080
of unit testing.

00:34:09.080 --> 00:34:11.360
And so I have trouble automating something

00:34:11.360 --> 00:34:13.639
I don't really know the ins and outs of.

00:34:13.639 --> 00:34:15.879
But in general, you'll spend less time debugging

00:34:15.879 --> 00:34:17.439
all of your parameterized code.

00:34:19.239 --> 00:34:20.479
But with that, you know,

00:34:20.479 --> 00:34:22.840
that's all I had to talk about like from a high level.

00:34:22.840 --> 00:34:25.120
So, I mean, feel free to ask questions

00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:27.399
about like the package itself,

00:34:27.399 --> 00:34:30.320
you know, the backend, how it's doing its things.

00:34:30.320 --> 00:34:33.800
But in general, Graveler allows like our new developers

00:34:33.800 --> 00:34:36.560
to, you know, start building dashboards right away.

00:34:36.560 --> 00:34:39.840
We have about like a two week onboarding period

00:34:39.840 --> 00:34:42.280
with, you know, like intermediate SQL and R training

00:34:42.280 --> 00:34:44.239
and then in-house training as well.

00:34:44.239 --> 00:34:45.439
And after the end of two weeks,

00:34:45.439 --> 00:34:47.719
we give them a week to build their first Graveler dashboard,

00:34:47.719 --> 00:34:49.120
that workflow.

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:52.760
And so, I mean, in the turnaround of 15 business days,

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:55.000
you have people building, you know,

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.040
some of the best, you know, shiny apps.

00:34:57.040 --> 00:34:59.520
Well, I guess not the best shiny apps you can make.

00:34:59.520 --> 00:35:02.959
Robust, shiny apps very, very quickly.

00:35:02.959 --> 00:35:04.919
So, huge shout out to RStudio as well.

00:35:04.919 --> 00:35:07.639
I mean, it itself was a game changer for us,

